Is the amount of a countrys alcohol consumption affected by how happy its citizens are?

In my dataset is a happiness factor ranking of countries around the world. This happiness ranking is based on certain variables such as freedom of expression, freedom of religion and economic freedom.

You would think that countries with higher religious restrictions would translate to low amounts of alcohol consumed per person per year. However, the plot above doesnt seem to support this assumption. As you can see, there is a slight positive trend but the data really shows that there really is not. Both positive and negative residuals are somewhat evenly distributed above and below the least of squares line and across the x-axis and are not tightly packed around the line. This suggests a low correlation score which suggests a weak correlation to a positive linear trend. This assumption is supported by the very low R-squared value of less than 1% (0.009635).
